'''Amanda Glassman''' is the vice president for programs, the director of global health policy, and a senior fellow at the [[Center for Global Development]].<ref name=guardian>{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/health-revolution/2016/mar/22/millions-saved-book-healthcare-global-aid-policy |title=Millions saved: how to make sure global health programs work |date=March 22, 2016 |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=cgdev-bio/>

"She has 20 years of experience working on health and social protection policy and programs in Latin America and elsewhere in the developing world"<ref name=guardian/>

==Early life==

Glassman's parents were [[foreign service officer]]s,<ref name=straight>{{cite web |url=http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/v17/n12/full/nm1211-1534.html |title=Straight talk with... Amanda Glassman |author=Elie Dolgin |date=December 6, 2011 |publisher=''[[Nature Medicine]]''}}</ref> so she lived in Cuba, Mexico, Argentina, and Russia throughout her childhood.<ref name="rbf-interview">{{cite web |url=https://www.rbfhealth.org/resource/rbf-perspectives-interview-amanda-glassman-conditional-cash-transfers-ccts |title=RBF Perspectives: Interview with Amanda Glassman on Conditional Cash Transfers (CCTs) |publisher=RBF Health |accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>

==Career==

Glassman received her BA at [[Brown University]] in 1992 and [[MSc]] at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]] in 1996.<ref name=cgdev-bio>{{cite web |url=http://www.cgdev.org/expert/amanda-glassman |title=Amanda Glassman |accessdate=June 2, 2016 |publisher=Center for Global Development}}</ref><ref name=linkedin>{{cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/amanda-glassman-6a276a8 |title=Amanda Glassman |publisher=[[LinkedIn]] |accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>

Glassman was the deputy director of the [[Global Health Financing Initiative]] at the [[Brookings Institution]] from 2006 to 2008.<ref name=linkedin/>

She was the Principal Technical Lead for Health at the [[Inter-American Development Bank]] (2008â€“2010),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americasquarterly.org/node/1676 |title=Amanda Glassman |accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=linkedin/> where she designed and evaluated public health programs including [[conditional cash transfer]] programs.<ref name=rbf-interview />

In October 2011, Glassman became the director of global health policy at the Center for Global Development.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Amanda_Glassman/info |title=Amanda Glassman - Info |publisher=Research Gate |accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>

==Work==

At the Center for Global Development, Glassman has worked on [[demand-side financing]] in Africa and incentives for health, as well as [[allocative efficiency]].<ref name=rbf-interview/>

She has also studied state-level health policy in large decentralized countries like India, Pakistan, and Nigeria. In contrast with the [[World Bank]] and other organizations that work at the national level in these countries, Glassman has worked at the state level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://files.givewell.org/files/conversations/Amanda%20Glassman%208-27-13.pdf |title=Conversation with Amanda Glassman on August 27, 2013 |publisher=[[GiveWell]] |accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>

